This paper focuses on self-supervised learning methods for representation learning in interactive environments, which is a topic that falls under the broad category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper specifically examines the effectiveness of these methods in visual environments, which suggests a focus on computer vision (cs.CV). Additionally, the evaluation of the learned representations in terms of their ability to capture true state information and generalize to novel situations suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and robotics (cs.RO). Finally, the visualization of the representations' focus on different parts of the environment suggests a potential focus on graphics (cs.GR).
